{"questionId":"20352","questionHtml":"<p>A Ferris wheel with diameter <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>110</mn></math> metres rotates at a constant speed. The lowest point on&nbsp;the wheel is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math> metres above the ground, as shown on the following diagram. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext></math> is a point on&nbsp;the wheel. The wheel starts moving with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext></math> at the lowest point and completes one revolution&nbsp;in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn></math> minutes.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/130a1a1c2dd7affe058b54480f42708775ab9602.png\"></p>\n<p>The height, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> metres, of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext></math> above the ground after <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> minutes is given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></math>,&nbsp;where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>∈</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>Find the values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>amplitude is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>110</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>55</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>55</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>65</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mi>b</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>55</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>20</mn><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>65</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>314</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"20352","referenceCode":"21M.2.SL.TZ1.4","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"A Ferris wheel with diameter 110 metres rotates at a constant speed. The lowest point on the wheel is 10 metres above the ground, as shown on the following diagram. P is a point on","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"4","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.7—Circular functions: graphs, composites, transformations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}